John Edward: Language skills essential for global citizens
Independent schools in Scotland have an outstanding record of academic excellence, and this has continued in 2018 with a series of further excellent exam results, as well as individual and collective success in sport, the arts, music and other community-wide initiatives.
With over 30,000 pupils in Scotland, these schools, represented by The Scottish Council of Independent Schools (SCIS), strive to provide the best service to their pupils and parents.
Independent schools aim to prepare their pupils for secondary and higher education, their chosen careers and their place as global citizens.
As an education sector that can design and implement a tailored school curriculum, we see that modern languages remain popular and desirable subjects of choice in schools.
Nelson Mandela said, "If you talk to someone in a language they understand, you hit their head.
When you talk to him in his own language, you reach his heart.
This is a powerful reminder that we cannot rely on English alone to build relationships and bonds of trust with people from other countries.
From the recent exam results this year, we can conclude that languages are at the top of the ranking, with the highest pass rates among independent schools.
In total, 68 percent of the students who studied foreign languages scored highly.
Data collected from 74 SCIS-affiliated schools showed that 72 percent of students scored high (A) in Mandarin, while 72 percent of students in German, 69 percent of students in French and 63 percent of students in Spanish also scored A.
This shows that independent schools in Scotland are supporting foreign languages as essential skills that children and young people will undoubtedly need in the future.
Languages are now given as much importance as STEM subjects (science, technology, engineering and mathematics) in independent school curricula and elsewhere.
A 2014 study by the UK Employment and Skills Commission found that 17 percent of the barriers to filling jobs were attributed to a lack of language skills, according to employers.
Language skills are therefore becoming increasingly important in preparing young people for their future careers.
As more and more jobs require language skills, these skills are essential in a globalised world.
Regardless of the career a person chooses, if he has learned a second language, he will have a real advantage in the future with such a skill for life.
Direct communication with people from abroad automatically gives a multilingual person an edge over the competition.
According to a YouGov poll of more than 4,000 British adults in 2013, 75 percent were not able to speak a foreign language well enough to engage in conversation, with French the only language that stood above 10 percent, with a total of 15 percent.
This is why investing in language education is important for today's children.
Being able to speak multiple languages, especially those of emerging economies, will give children a better chance of finding meaningful jobs.
In Scotland, schools choose which languages they teach.
Some schools will focus on the more classical modern languages, while other schools will teach languages that are most important to the UK as they look ahead to 2020, such as Mandarin or Japanese.
Whatever your child's interests, there will always be a variety of languages to choose from in independent schools, with teachers who are specialists in this field.
Scottish independent schools are committed to providing a learning environment that prepares children and gives them the skills they need to succeed, whatever their future.
It cannot be denied at present that languages remain vital to the future of the country in a global business environment, so this must be reflected in education.
Modern languages should in fact be considered as 'international communication skills'.
Independent schools will continue to offer this choice, diversity and excellence to young people in Scotland.
It has to be done.
John Edward is Director of the Scottish Council of Independent Schools
