Harvard students take a course on the importance of adequate rest
A new course at Harvard University this year is getting all students to get more sleep in an effort to combat the growing macho culture where it seems cool to study all night and drink a lot of caffeine.
One professor found that students at the world's largest university often have no idea of the basic principles of self-care.
Charles Czeisler, professor of sleep medicine at Harvard Medical School, a specialist affiliated with Brigham and Women's Hospital, created the course, which, as far as he knows, is unique in the United States.
He got the idea to start the course after giving a talk on the impact of sleep deprivation on learning.
"At the end of my talk, a girl came up to me and said, 'Why am I only hearing this now, in my senior year?'
She said that no one had ever told her how important sleep was, which surprised me", he told The Telegraph.
The course, which is being offered for the first time this year, will explain to students the basics of how good sleep habits help improve academic and athletic performance and also promote their overall well-being.
Paul Barreira, professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and executive director of the university's health services, said the university decided to host the course when it was determined that students were severely sleep deprived during the week.
The course lasts one hour and includes a series of interactive tasks.
In one of the sections, students see a picture of a dorm room, where they click on coffee cups, curtains, exercise machines and books to learn about the effects of caffeine and light and how sports performance is affected by sleep deprivation, and the importance of a bedtime routine.
In another part, participants will learn how sleep deprivation increases the long-term risk of heart attack, stroke, depression, and cancer.
Using a campus map, with interactive icons, participants are encouraged to reflect on their daily routine.
We know that this will not change the behaviour of students immediately.
But we believe they have a right to know all this, just as people have a right to know what the effects of their choice of cigarettes are on their health, Czeisler added.
The culture of one-night stands, he says, is still alive, and modern technology and increasing pressure on students have made sleep deprivation a growing problem.
Getting enough, good-quality sleep should be the student's "secret weapon" to combat stress, fatigue, and anxiety, he said, and even to prevent weight gain, since lack of sleep causes the brain to give them a constant feeling of hunger.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old from California who is studying chemical and physical biology, helped Professor Czeisler to write the course, having taken lessons from the professor last year when he was a first-year student at Harvard.
He said the course had opened his eyes and inspired him to make the course available to everyone on campus.
The next step, he hopes, is to ask all students to follow a similar curriculum before coming to the competing institution.
Professor Czeisler advises students to set an alarm for bedtime, not just an alarm for getting up, but also to be aware of the harmful effects of the "blue light" from electronic screens and LED lights, which can disrupt your circadian rhythm, making it difficult to fall asleep.
