In the vast majority of new cases, the diseases were transmitted through sex, which was not the case before.
HIV has spread rapidly in some parts of China in the past through transfusions of contaminated blood.
But the number of people infected with HIV in this way is now almost zero, Chinese health officials said at a conference in Yunnan province.
However, compared with the same period last year, the number of people living with HIV and AIDS in China has increased by 100,000.
HIV transmission through sex is an acute problem in the Chinese LGBT community.
Homosexuality has been decriminalized in China since 1997, but discrimination against LGBT people is reportedly widespread.
Because of the conservative values of the country, studies estimate that 70 to 90 percent of men who have sex with men will eventually marry a woman.
Often the diseases are transmitted through inadequate protection during sexual relations in these relationships.
Since 2003, the Chinese government has promised universal access to HIV medication as part of efforts to address the problem.
