The inventor of the World Wide Web is planning a new Internet to take on Google and Facebook
Tim Berners-Lee, the inventor of the World Wide Web, is starting a startup that wants to compete with Facebook, Amazon and Google.
Inrupt, the latest project from the tech legend, is a company that is based on the open source platform Solid by Berners-Lee.
Solid offers users the ability to choose where their data is stored and who can access what information.
In an exclusive interview with Fast Company, Berners-Lee joked that "world domination" is the guiding idea behind Inrupt.
"We need to do this now", he said about the startup.
"This is a historic moment".
The app uses Solid's technology to allow people to create their own 'personal online data store' or POD.
It can store contact lists, activity lists, an agenda, a music library and other personal and professional tools.
It's like Google Drive, Microsoft Outlook, Slack and Spotify are all available together through one browser and all at the same time.
What makes POD unique is the fact that it is entirely up to the user who has access to what information.
The company calls this "personal empowerment through data".
The idea behind Inrupt, according to CEO John Bruce, is that the company provides the resources, processes and skills needed to make Solid available to everyone.
The company currently consists of Berners-Lee, Bruce, a security platform that was bought by IBM, a few developers who were contracted to work on the project, and a community of volunteer programmers.
Starting this week, technology developers around the world will be able to create their own decentralized apps using the tools available on the Inrupt website.
Berners-Lee said that he and his team will not hold talks with "Facebook and Google about whether or not to introduce a complete transformation that completely turns all their business models upside down at once".
"We're not asking for their permission".
In a post on Medium published on Saturday, Berners-Lee wrote that the "mission (of Inrupt) is to provide the commercial power and an ecosystem that helps protect the integrity and quality of the new web, which is being built on Solid".
In 1994, Berners-Lee transformed the Internet when he founded the World Wide Web Consortium at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology.
In recent months, Berners-Lee has been an influential voice in the debate over net neutrality.
Even after the launch of Inrupt, Berners-Lee will remain as founder and director of the World Wide Web Consortium, the Web Foundation and the Open Data Institute.
"I'm incredibly optimistic about this new era for the web", Berners-Lee added.
