He later stormed into the line of fire and led the line forward before running alone into a field gun and knocking out three members of the detachment.
Lieutenant Colonel Vann was killed by a German sniper on October 4, 1918, just over a month before the end of the war.
Michael Vann, 72, said that his grandfather's actions were "something I know I can never touch, but also something that makes me feel humbled".
He and his brother Dr. James Vann also laid a wreath after the parade led by the Brentwood Imperial Youth Band.
Michael Vann said that he was "very honoured to be able to play a part in the parade", adding that "the courage of a real hero is shown by the support he receives from a large number of people".
MMA fans stayed up all night to watch Bellator 206 and got Peppa Pig instead.
Imagine, you've been up all night watching a stalked Bellator 206 and you miss the most important moment.
The San Jose poster listed 13 fights, including six in the main section, and it was broadcast all night in the United Kingdom on Channel 5.
At 6:00 a.m., just as Gegard Mousasi and Rory MacDonald were preparing for their fight, viewers in the United Kingdom were unpleasantly surprised when the station switched to Peppa Pig.
Some were outraged because they had stayed up all night for this fight.
One fan described the transition to the children's program on Twitter as "a bad joke".
"Government regulations prohibit showing content that is not suitable for children after 6:00 a.m., and therefore we had to switch to the children's program", said Dave Schwartz, senior vice president of marketing and communications at Bellator, when asked about the broadcast.
"Peppa the pig, "yes".
Scott Coker, the company president of Bellator, said they will be adjusting their programming to ensure that UK viewers have a chance in the future.
"I think, in view of the fight back, we can solve this problem", Coker said.
"But it's six o'clock in the morning here on a Sunday and we can't discuss anything until Sunday our time, Monday their time.
We're working on it.
When I made the switch, there were a lot of texts going back and forth, and believe me, not all of them were as friendly.
We tried to fix it, we thought it was a technical problem.
But it wasn't. It was a government problem.
I can promise you this won't happen a second time.
We're limiting the broadcasts to five nights instead of six, as we normally do, we tried to make it even better for the fans, but we just went too far.
It is an unfortunate situation".
Tom Daley felt "inferior" because of his sexual orientation
Olympic show jumper Tom Daley says that during his youth he felt inferior because of his sexual orientation, but that this gave him the motivation to succeed.
The 24-year-old said that it was not until he entered secondary school that he realized that "not everyone is like me".
In an interview with Desert Island Discs on Radio 4 with Lauren Laverne, he said he spoke out about gay rights to give others "hope".
He also said that parenting had contributed to his decreasing appreciation of winning at the Olympics.
Kirsty Young, the regular host of the long-running show has taken a few months off due to illness.
Appearing as a freak on Laverne's first program, Daley told that during his youth he felt "less" than others because it was "not socially accepted to like both girls and boys".
He said: "To this day, those feelings, the feeling of being less and the feeling of being different, are real facts that have given me the strength to be successful".
He wanted to prove that he was "something" so that people would not be disappointed if they eventually found out about his orientation.
The two-time Olympic bronze medalist has become a prominent campaigner for the LGBT community and used his presence at this year's Commonwealth Games in Australia to call on more countries to decriminalise homosexuality.
He said that he spoke out because he felt happy to be able to live openly without further consequences and to give others "hope".
The three-time world champion said that the fact that he fell in love with a man, American filmmaker Dustin Lance Back, whom he met in 2013, "completely surprised me".
Daley married the Oscar winner last year, who is 20 years older than him, but said the age difference had never been an issue.
"When you have to go through so much at such a young age", he said, "he took part in his first Olympics at 14 and his father died of cancer three years later, it's hard to find anyone in your own age group who has gone through the same ups and downs.
The couple became parents in June of a son named Robert Ray Black-Daley, and Daley said his "entire perspective" had changed.
"If you had asked me this question last year, I would have said it was all about winning a gold medal", he said.
"But you know what, there are more important things on earth than winning Olympic gold medals.
My Olympic gold medal is Robbie".
His son shares the same name as his father who died in 2011 at the age of 40 after being diagnosed with brain cancer.
Daley said that his father hadn't accepted that he was going to die and one of the last things he asked was if they had already gotten the tickets to London 2012 because he wanted to sit in the front row.
"I couldn't get it over my heart to say, 'You won't be there to sit in the front row, Dad,'" he said.
"I held his hand when he stopped breathing and it wasn't until his breathing actually stopped and he died that I finally recognized that he wasn't invincible", he said.
The following year, Daley competed in the 2012 Olympics and won bronze.
"I knew I had dreamed of this all my life, diving in front of a home crowd during the Olympics, there's no better feeling", he said.
It was also the inspiration for his first musical choice, Proud by Heather Small, which had gripped him strongly on the way to the games and which still gave him goose bumps.
Desert Island Discs is available to listen to on BBC Radio 4 on Sunday at 11:15 BST.
Mickelson, not in shape, on the bench during the Ryder Cup on Saturday.
American Phil Mickelson will set a record when he plays his 47th Ryder Cup match on Sunday, but he'll have to get back into shape before it becomes a sad milestone.
Mickelson, competing in the biennial event for the 12th time, a record, was benched by team captain Jim Furyk for the fourballs and foursomes on Saturday.
Instead of being in the center of the action, as he has often done for the United States, the winner of five majors splits the day between supporting his teammates and practicing on the driving range, trying to figure out what's wrong with him.
Because he was never known for his straight drives even at the peak of his career, the 48-year-old is not the ideal choice for the tight fairways of Le Golf National, where the long grass of the roughs routinely punishes stray balls.
And if the course itself isn't daunting enough, Mickelson will face the ever-accurate Francesco Molinari, British Open champion, in the ninth match on Sunday, who is tied with rookie Tommy Fleetwood to win all four matches this week.
If the Americans, who are four points behind at the start of the 12 singles matches, get off to a good start, Mickelson's match could be absolutely crucial.
Furyk has shown confidence in this man, though frankly he could hardly have it any other way.
"He fully understood the role he had today, slapped me on the back, put his arm around me and said he was ready for tomorrow", Furyk said.
"He's very confident in himself.
He's been inducted into the Hall of Fame and he's contributed so much to these teams, in the past, but also this week.
I probably didn't expect him to play two games.
I expected more, but it is what it is, and it is the way we thought we should have acted.
He wants to be there, just like everyone else".
Mickelson could beat Nick Faldo's record for most Ryder Cup games played on Sunday.
It could also mean the end of a Ryder Cup career in which he never quite matched the high points of his personal career.
Mickelson has 18 wins, 20 losses and 7 draws to his name, but Furyk said his presence had a certain intangible impact on the team.
"He's funny, he's sarcastic, he's witty, he likes to make jokes with people and he's a great guy to have on the team", he explained.
"I think the younger players enjoyed playing him occasionally last week, which was fun to watch.
He has so much more to offer than just his game".
Thomas Bjorn, captain of the European team, knows that a big lead can quickly vanish.
Thomas Bjorn, the captain of the European team, knows from experience that the comfortable lead before the singles matches on the final day of the Ryder Cup can easily turn into a less comfortable situation.
The Dane made his debut in the 1997 race in Valderrama, where the team captained by Seve Ballesteros had a five-point lead over the Americans, but eventually crossed the finish line with the smallest possible margin: 141⁄2-131⁄2.
"You keep reminding yourself that we had a big lead in Valderrama; we had a big lead in Brookline, where we lost, and in Valderrama, where we won, but just", Bjorn said, disconnected here, after watching the 2018 Lightning win 5-3 on Friday and yesterday, good for a 10-6 lead over Le Golf National.
So history shows me and everyone else on the team that this is not a game that's been played.
Everyone will have to put in their full effort tomorrow.
Get to work and execute the plan properly.
It's not over until the dots are on the board.
We have a goal, and that is to win this trophy, and we need to stay focused on that.
I keep saying, I focus on the 12 players we have, but we're also aware of the people on the other side, some of the best players in the world".
Enthusiastic about his players' performance on a difficult golf course, Bjorn added: "I would never get ahead of myself in this area.
Tomorrow, we'll have another challenge.
Tomorrow we're gonna be talking about individual achievement, and that's another entirely different discipline.
It's great to be out there with a partner when things are going well, but when you're out there alone, your skills as a golfer are really tested.
That's the message you have to give the players, try to make the best of yourself tomorrow.
So now let your partner go and let him make the best of himself".
Unlike Bjorn, his opponent, Jim Furyk, expects his players to perform better individually than as partners.
Furyk himself has experience with both sides of this turnaround on the final day, as a member of the winning team in Brookline and as a loser when Europe realized the "Miracle of Medina".
"I remember every damn word of that speech", he said in response to a question about how Ben Crenshaw, the 1999 captain, had cheered his players up for the final day.
"We have 12 big games tomorrow, but let's try to get off to a good start, like in Brookline, or like in Medina.
When we have the momentum, there's a lot of pressure on the midfield matches.
We've aligned our lineup to this and we're sending the guys out in the order that we think is best and, you know, we're going to try to do something out of the blue tomorrow".
Thomas is tasked with trying to lead the counter-offensive and puts Rory McIlroy in for the first match, and Paul Casey, Justin Rose, Jon Rahm, Tommy Fleetwood and Ian Poulter are the other Europeans in the first half of the batting order.
"I chose this group in this order because I think we are so constantly covered", Bjorn said of his selection of singles players.
Germany's new warship delayed again
The German Navy's newest frigate was supposed to enter service in 2014, replacing the outdated warships of the Cold War era, but it will take at least another year to be ready, due to faulty systems and rising costs, local media reported.
The commissioning of the 'Rheinland-Pfalz', the lead ship in the brand new Baden-Wuerttemberg-class frigates, has now been postponed to the first half of 2019, according to the newspaper Die Zeit quoting a military spokesman.
The vessel was due to join the Navy in 2014, but troubling problems after delivery have plagued the fate of the ambitious project.
The four Baden-Wuerttemberg-class vessels ordered by the Navy in 2007 are intended to replace the obsolete Bremen-class frigates.
As far as we know, they have a powerful cannon, a series of anti-aircraft and anti-ship missiles, and some form of stealth technology, such as reduced radar, infrared and acoustic characteristics.
Other important features are longer maintenance cycles, it should be possible to deploy the latest frigates for up to two consecutive years, away from home ports.
The continuing delays, however, mean that the advanced warships, designed to enable Germany to project its power overseas, are already outdated by the time they are commissioned, notes Die Zeit.
The fateful frigate F125 made headlines last year when the German Navy officially refused to commission the vessel and sent it back to the Blohm & Voss shipyard in Hamburg.
This was the first time the Navy had sent a ship back to a shipbuilder after delivery.
Little is known about the reasons behind this return, but German media cited a number of crucial "software and hardware flaws" that would render the warship useless if deployed on a combat mission.
Software defects were particularly important as the Baden-Wuerttemberg-class vessels are operated by a crew of about 120 sailors, half the manpower on the older Bremen-class frigates.
It was also revealed that the ship is severely overweight, which will reduce performance and limit the Navy's ability to carry out further upgrades.
The Rhineland-Palatinate weighs 7,000 tons, which is twice as much as the ships of a similar class used by the Germans in World War II.
In addition to the faulty hardware, the cost of the entire project, including the training of the crew, is also a problem.
It is said that this has reached a staggering €3.1 billion, compared to the original €2.2 billion.
The problems facing the newest frigates are made all the more serious by recent warnings that the power of the German navy is declining.
Earlier this year Hans-Peter Bartels, head of the parliamentary defense committee in Germany, acknowledged that the navy actually has "a shortage of deployable ships".
The official said the problem has grown like a snowball over time, as old ships have been decommissioned but no replacement vessels have been delivered.
He complained that none of the Baden-Wuerttemberg class frigates were yet available for entry into the navy.
The National Trust is eavesdropping on the secret lives of bats.
New research being conducted on a farm in the Scottish Highlands is trying to reveal how bats use the landscape in their search for food.
The hope is that the findings will shed new light on the behavior of these unique flying mammals and contribute to future conservation efforts.
The study, carried out by scientists from the National Trust for Scotland, tracks the common and small dwarf bat, the brown giant bat and the water bat at Inverewe Gardens in Wester Ross.
Special recording equipment is placed at key locations around the property to monitor the activity of the bats throughout the season.
NTS staff and volunteers will also carry out mobile surveys using handheld fingerprint sensors.
Expert sound analysis of all recordings will determine the frequency of the bat's cries and which species is doing what.
A habitat map and a report are then produced to provide a detailed landscape-scale picture of their behaviour.
Rob Dewar, a conservation adviser at the NTS, hopes the results will show which areas of the habitat are most important for bats and how they are used by the species.
This information will help to determine the benefits of habitat management, such as creating grasslands and how best to maintain forests for bats and similar species.
Bat populations in Scotland and the rest of the UK have declined significantly over the last century.
They are threatened by construction and development activities that affect their habitat and habitat loss.
Wind turbines and lightning can also pose a risk, as can fly-traps and certain chemical treatments of building materials and attacks by domestic cats.
Bats are not actually blind.
However, their nocturnal hunting habits make their ears more useful than their eyes when it comes to catching prey.
They use advanced echo-location technology to determine the position of insects and obstacles in their flight path.
The NTS, which is responsible for the care of more than 270 historic buildings, 38 important gardens, and 76,000 acres of land in the country, takes bats very seriously.
The NTS has ten trained experts who regularly carry out surveys, inspections of accommodation and sometimes rescue operations.
The organization even established the first and only bat reserve in Scotland at Threave Estate in Dumfries and Galloway, home to eight of Scotland's ten bat species.
Landscape manager David Thompson says the estate is the ideal territory for the bats.
"Here in Threave, we have a great environment for bats", he said.
"We have the old buildings, many very old trees and the right habitat.
But there is still so much that is unknown about bats, and so the work we are doing here and in other locations will help us to better understand what they need to thrive".
He stresses the importance of bat control before maintenance work is carried out, as the possible unintentional destruction of a nesting site could lead to the death of 400 female bats and their young, potentially wiping out an entire local population.
Bats are a protected species and it is illegal to kill, harass or disturb them or destroy their habitat.
Elisabeth Ferrell, Scotland's official for the Bat Conservation Trust, has asked the public to contribute to help.
She said, "We still have a lot to learn about our bats, and of many of our species, we simply don't know what's going on with their populations".
Ronaldo rejects assault charges as his lawyers prepare to sue a German magazine
Cristiano Ronaldo called the sexual assault allegations "fake news" and said people "want to promote themselves" by using his name.
His lawyers are about to sue the German weekly Der Spiegel, which published the charges.
The Portugal and Juventus striker is accused of assaulting an American woman named Kathryn Mayorga in a Las Vegas hotel room in 2009.
He is also accused of paying her $375,000 to keep quiet about the incident, Der Spiegel reported on Friday.
