Brexit: UK 'will regret it forever' if carmakers leave
The UK will 'regret it forever' if it loses its status as the world leader in car production after Brexit, said Economic Affairs Secretary Greg Clark.
He added that it was "worrying" that Toyota UK had told the BBC that if Britain left the EU without a deal, the company would temporarily stop production at its Burnaston plant near Derby.
"We need a deal", Clark said.
The Japanese carmaker said the impact of delays at the border in the event of a no-deal Brexit would cost jobs.
The Burnaston plant, where Toyota's Auris and Avensis are made, produced almost 150,000 cars last year, 90% of which were exported to other countries in the European Union.
"My view is that if Britain crashes out of the EU at the end of March, we will see production at our factory come to a halt", said Marvin Cooke, Toyota's managing director in Burnaston.
Other UK carmakers, including Honda, BMW and Jaguar Land Rover, have also expressed concerns about the impact of leaving the EU without an agreement on the functioning of cross-border trade.
For example, BMW has already announced that it will close its Mini factory in Oxford for a month after Brexit.
The most worrying concern for carmakers is the risks in the supply chain in the event of a no-deal Brexit.
Toyota's production line operates on the 'just-in-time' principle, with parts arriving every 37 minutes from suppliers in the UK and EU for cars made to order.
If the UK leaves the EU on 29 March without a deal, there could be border unrest that industry says could lead to delays and shortages of parts.
Toyota cannot stock up more than one day's supply at its Derbyshire plant, the company said, and therefore production would be halted in that case.
Clark said Theresa May's Chequers plan for the future relationship with the EU was "exactly aligned to avoid those border checks".
"We need to have a deal.We want to have the best deal, which will not only allow us to continue the current success but also to seize this opportunity", he told listeners of BBC Radio 4's Today programme.
"The proof, not only from Toyota but also from other manufacturers, is that we absolutely must be able to continue with this very successful set of supply chains".
Toyota could not say how long production would be halted, but warned in the longer term that the additional costs would affect the company's competitive position and that this would ultimately cost jobs.
Peter Tsouvallaris, a 24-year Burnaston employee and representative of the Unite union at the plant, said that his members are growing increasingly concerned: "In my experience, once these jobs are lost, they never come back.
A government spokesman said: "We have presented a precise and credible plan for our future relationship with the EU".
Trump-Rosenstein meeting may be delayed again, says White House
The crucial meeting between Donald Trump and Deputy Attorney General Rod Rosenstein may be "postponed for another week" as the fight over Supreme Court nominee Brett Kavanaugh continues, the White House said Sunday.
Rosenstein oversees the work of special counsel Robert Mueller, who is investigating Russian influence in the election, ties between Trump aides and Russia, and possible obstruction of justice by the president.
The question of whether Trump will fire the deputy attorney general and thereby jeopardize Mueller's independence has been running in the Washington gossip machine for months.
Earlier this month, the New York Times reported that Rosenstein had discussed the possibility of wearing a microphone to record conversations with Trump and to impeach the president via the 25th Amendment.
Rosenstein denied this report.
But when he went to the White House last Monday, rumors were circulating that he was about to resign.
Instead, a meeting with Trump, who was then at the United Nations in New York, was announced for Thursday.
Trump said he "would rather not" fire Rosenstein, but then moved the meeting to avoid a conflict with a Senate Judiciary Committee hearing in which Kavanaugh and one of the women who accused him of sexual misconduct, Dr. Christine Blasey Ford, were both scheduled to testify.
On Friday, Trump ordered the FBI to conduct a week-long investigation into the allegations against Kavanaugh, delaying the vote in the full Senate once again.
On Sunday, Sarah Sanders, Trump's press secretary, appeared on Fox News.
Asked about the meeting with Rosenstein, she said: "There is no date set yet, it could be this week, but it could also be postponed another week, given all the other things going on with the Supreme Court.
But we'll see and I always like to keep the press informed".
Some reporters had trouble with this claim: Sanders has not held a press conference at the White House since September 10.
Host Chris Wallace asked her why.
Sanders said the lack of press conferences was not caused by a dislike of the "attention-grabbing" TV journalists, though, she added, "I won't deny they're trying to get attention".
She then suggested that direct contact between Trump and the press would increase.
"The president does more Q&A sessions than any president before him", she said, without providing any evidence: "We looked at the numbers".
Press conferences will still take place, Sanders said, but "if the press has the opportunity to ask the president of the United States questions directly, that's infinitely better than talking to me.
We try to do that a lot and you've seen us do that a lot in the last few weeks and that will take the place of a press conference when you can talk to the president of the United States".
Trump regularly answers questions when he leaves the White House or when he participates in public sessions or during press conferences with visiting dignitaries.
Press conferences with only the president are rare.
In New York this week, the president may have demonstrated why, by making a candid and at times bizarre appearance to the assembled reporters.
Health Minister writes letter on Brexit to NHS Scotland workers from other EU countries
The Secretary of State for Health has written to EU staff working at NHS Scotland to express the country's gratitude and wishes for them to continue working at the NHS after Brexit.
Jeane Freeman, MSP, sent a letter with less than six months to go before the UK withdraws from the EU.
The Scottish Government has already agreed to bear the costs of applying for permanent status for EU citizens working for the devolved public services.
In her letter, Freeman wrote: "During the summer, negotiations between the UK and the EU continued, and this autumn the expected decisions will be taken.
But at the same time the UK government has also stepped up preparations for a possible no-deal scenario.
I know these must be uncertain times for all of you.
I therefore want to reiterate how much I appreciate the contribution of all staff, regardless of their nationality.
Colleagues from across the EU and beyond, bring in valuable experience and skills that strengthen and improve the work of the NHS and that deliver benefits to patients and the communities we serve.
Scotland is definitely your home and we want you to stay here".
Christion Abercrombie undergoes emergency surgery after suffering a head injury
Tennessee State Tigers linebacker Christion Abercrombie underwent emergency surgery yesterday after sustaining a head injury in the 31-27 loss to the Vanderbilt Commodores, reports Mike Organ of the Tennessean.
Rod Reed, Tennessee State's head coach, told reporters the accident happened shortly before recess.
"He came to the sideline and kind of collapsed there", Reed said.
The trainers and medical staff immediately gave Abercrombie oxygen on the sideline before putting him on a stretcher and taking him away for further examination.
A Tennessee State official told Chris Harris of WSMV in Nashville, Tennessee, that Abercrombie had come out of the operating room at Vanderbilt Medical Center.
Harris added that "no details are known about the type/size of the injury yet" and Tennessee State is trying to figure out when the injury occurred.
