He was tackled a total of five times on Saturday before leaving the field, making him a total of 18 tackles this season.
Foreign buyers will have to pay higher levies when buying a house in the UK
Foreign buyers will have to pay higher levies when buying a house in the UK and the proceeds will be used to help the homeless under new plans by the Conservatives
This action will have to neutralize Corbyn's success to attract young voters.
The increase in levy is levied on persons who do not pay tax in the UK
The Treasury expects this to raise £120 million a year to help the homeless.
Foreign buyers will have to pay higher levies when buying a home in the UK and the extra proceeds will be used to help the homeless, Theresa May will announce today.
This action is seen as an attempt to neutralize the success of Jeremy Corbyn who is attracting young voters with promises to provide more affordable housing and pass it on to high earners.
The levy increase is levied on individuals and firms who do not pay tax in the UK, with the extra proceeds being spent in a government effort to combat homelessness.
The surcharge, which is in addition to the current levy, including the higher rates introduced two years ago for second homes and homes bought for rent, could be as high as 3%.
The Treasury expects to raise up to £120 million a year.
An estimated 13 percent of new homes in London are bought by non-UK residents, driving up prices and making it difficult for newcomers to get a foot on the housing ladder.
Many affluent areas of the country, especially in the capital, have become practically 'ghost towns' because of the high number of foreign buyers who spend most of their time outside the country.
This new policy comes just weeks after Boris Johnson called for a reduction in the levy to help young people buy their first home.
He accused big construction firms of keeping prices high by buying up land and not using it and he called on May to abolish quotas on affordable housing to repair Britain's 'housing scandal'.
Corbyn has announced a remarkable series of housing reforms, including rent caps and an end to evictions "without negligence".
He also wants to give local governments more opportunities to build new homes.
May said: "Last year I said I wanted to devote my time as Prime Minister to restoring the 'British Dream', that life would be better for each new generation.
And that means we have to fix our broken housing market.
Britain will always be open to people who want to live, work and build a life here.
However, it cannot be that it is as easy for non-UK residents and foreign companies to buy here as it is for hardworking British residents.
For too many people, the dream of owning a home has become too vague, and the humiliation of living without a roof over your head is already too real".
Jack Ross: 'My ultimate ambition is to manage Scotland'
Jack Ross, the manager of Sunderland, says it is his "ultimate ambition" to one day manage Scotland.
The Scot, 42, is enjoying the challenge of reviving the club from the north-east of England, who are currently third in League One, three points off first place.
He moved to the Stadium of Light last summer after guiding St Mirren back to the Scottish Premiership last season.
"As a footballer, I always wanted to play for my country.
But I was selected for the B team and that was the end of it", Ross told BBC Scotland's Sportsound.
"When I was a child, my father and I often watched Scotland play at Hampden Park and it's something that still attracts me.
However, that opportunity would come only if I was successful in managing a club".
Ross's predecessors as Sunderland managers include Dick Advocate, David Moyes, Sam Allardyce, Martin O'Neill, Roy Keane, Gus Poyet and Paulo Di Canio.
The former Alloa Athletic boss says he was not intimidated to become the successor to these established names at a big club, having previously turned down offers from Barnsley and Ipswich Town.
"Success for me right now is measured by 'can I get this club back into the Premier League?'
Because of the structure and facilities at this club, it should undoubtedly be in the Premier League", he says.
"It is not an easy task to achieve this, but I can only consider myself successful if I can get the club back there".
Ross has only been in his managerial career for three years, after a spell as assistant manager at Dumbarton and 15 months in the Hearts coaching group.
He then helped Alloa recover from relegation to the Third Division and transformed St Mirren from being on the verge of relegation to winning the Championship the following season.
And Ross says he feels more comfortable now than he ever did during his football career at Clyde, Hartlepool, Falkirk, St Mirren and Hamilton Academical.
"It was probably a real crossroads", he recalled from the moment he took over at Alloa.
"I really believed management was the right choice for me, much more than playing.
It sounds weird, because I did pretty well, I made pretty good money, and I had some pretty good highs.
But football can be tough.
There are a lot of things you face every week.
I still do, given the stress and the pressure of the job, but management just feels good.
I've always wanted to be a manager, and now that I'm really one, I feel more comfortable in my skin than I've ever felt in my adult life".
You can listen to the full interview on Sportsound on Sunday, September 30th, on Radio Scotland between 12:00 and 13:00 BST.
The perfect time for a pint is 5:30 p.m. on a Saturday, research reveals
The summer heat wave has boosted revenues for British pubs struggling to survive, but has also put more pressure on restaurant chains.
Groups with pubs and bars saw sales rise 2.7 percent in July, but restaurant revenues were down 4.8 percent, the figures show.
Peter Martin, of the business consultancy CGA, which compiled the figures, said: "Continued sunshine and the fact that England was in the world championships longer than expected meant that July showed a similar pattern to June, when pubs had a 2.8 percent increase in sales, with the difference that restaurants were now hit even harder.
The 1.8 percent drop in restaurant sales in June only got worse in July.
Pubs and bars focused on liquor sales performed by far the best, with better like-for-like growth than restaurants declined.
Pubs that are also focused on selling food also take advantage of the sun, but not as dramatically as the restaurants.
It looks like people were just going out to drink.
In pubs and bars under management, beverage sales were up 6.6 percent for the month, while food sales were down 3 percent".
