Red glow update: concentrations are decreasing in Pinellas, Manatee and Sarasota counties.
The most recent report from the Florida Fish and Wildlife Conservation Commission shows a general decline in red glow concentrations in parts of the Tampa Bay Area (located on the west coast of Florida in the United States).
According to the committee, there are reports of fragmentary increases in Red Glow in Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Charlotte and Collier counties, which could indicate a decline in concentrations.
The Red Glow extends an average of 200 kilometers of coastline, from Pinellas County in the north to Lee County in the south.
There are about 10 miles of coastline in Hillsborough County, but less spots than last week.
There's also been a report of red glow in Pasco County.
There have been medium concentrations reported off the coast of Pinellas County over the past week, low to high concentrations off the coast of Hillsborough County, background to high concentrations in Manatee County, background to high concentrations off or off the coast of Sarasota County, background to high concentrations in Charlotte County, background to high concentrations off or off the coast of Lee County, and low concentrations in Collier County.
